[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Voice Reviewer
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What's Done Well
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The Problem section is outstanding: passionate, specific, makes the reader feel the clinical tension ("Patient A metabolizes oxaliplatin twice as fast as Patient B")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The engineer-explaining-something-cool tone is consistent throughout ("This is a sequential decision problem under uncertainty with delayed, noisy rewards. That's exactly what reinforcement learning was designed for.")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Self-deprecating honesty in the Honest Take ("the RL algorithms are not the bottleneck... You'll spend 80% of your time on data engineering and 20% on the actual RL")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Parenthetical asides used effectively ("(ok, this is a gross oversimplification, but stay with me)" energy throughout)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The 70/30 vendor balance is excellent: the entire Technology section, MDP formulation, offline RL explanation, and general architecture are completely vendor-agnostic. AWS appears only in the implementation section.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" section is refreshingly honest for a cookbook recipe
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Clinical domain knowledge is woven naturally into the narrative rather than presented as dry reference material
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The reward function explanation is pedagogically excellent: "Two equally valid reward functions with different toxicity-efficacy tradeoff weights will produce meaningfully different policies. This isn't a bug; it's a feature."
