[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Location:** "The State of the Field" subsection, final paragraph
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The problem:** "Current approaches to validation include: importance-weighted evaluation (estimating policy value from historical data), simulation with pharmacokinetic/pharmacodynamic (PK/PD) models, and expert review of recommended actions." This sentence reads slightly more like a survey paper than an engineer explaining something. The rest of the section maintains the conversational register well.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Suggested fix:** Minor. Consider: "So how do you validate a policy you can't test on patients? Three approaches, none perfect: importance-weighted evaluation (estimate what would have happened using historical data), simulation with PK/PD models (build a fake patient and test on them), and expert review (show oncologists the recommendations and ask 'would you do this?')."
